The movement of the swimming larvae was similar to the breaststroke, creating a sinusoidal wave. Second to eighth abdominal segments were exposed to the air through back swimming. The sequence of movements during swimming were as follows: 1) larval body 
0.3 cm
under the surface, parallel with surface, pygopodium held vertically in contact with surface, prothorax sank a little, thoracic legs continually sculled backward at the surface (
Fig. 2a
); 2) prothorax continually sank and formed radian with abdomen, accumulating force to rebound eighth abdominal segment in contact with air (
Fig. 2b
); 3) mesothorax and metathorax started to sink, the radian became smaller and eighth abdominal segment became to expose to air (
Fig. 2c
); 4) the eighth abdominal segment shrank forward, made the whole larval body into the shape of an ‘‘ S ’’ (
Fig. 2d
); 5) tightened of the thorax and abdomen quick released to make the eighth abdominal segment heighter than surface, and also pulled sixth to seventh

abdominal segments to the surface (
Fig. 2e
); 6) after the sixth to eighth abdominal segments shrank forward maximally and then released quickly, and second to fifth abdominal segments were rebound to the air by inertia (

Fig. 2f– 
2g

); 7) thorax and abdomen returned to the starting position when sixth to eighth abdominal segments released.

